<taxonomicName authorityName="Bulycheva, 1955:" authorityYear="1050" box="[426,567,1609,1632]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeca">
<emphasis box="[426,567,1609,1632]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Vibilia caeca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Tasman Sea, AM P39760. Female, 6.1 mm. A, lateral view. Scale bars = 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (remainder).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="63.[264,1323,1758,1904]" box="[264,366,1758,1783]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis box="[264,366,1758,1783]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[264,1323,1758,1904]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
This species most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[752,885,1798,1823]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[752,885,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">V. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the absence of eyes is a unique feature amongst species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1830" box="[583,661,1838,1863]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[583,661,1838,1863]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Vibilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[264,1323,1758,1904]" box="[312,979,1878,1904]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">The salp associate has not been recorded for this species.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,1323,284,470]" box="[264,407,284,309]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis box="[264,407,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,1323,284,470]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
This species is only known from a few records from the northern Pacific Ocean, the northern Indian Ocean, the southwestern part of the Bering Sea and Kuril Islands (Bussol Strait), and the Tasman Sea. I have also collected it recently from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1082,1201,404,430]" name="Saint Pierre and Miquelon" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">San Pedro</collectingCountry>
Basin, off Los Angeles, California.
</paragraph>
